Here’s a step-by-step guide tailored to your details for creating and using an SSH key with your GitHub account on macOS:

* Open Terminal (press Cmd + Space, type “Terminal”)

* Check if you already have an SSH key:

```bash
ls -al ~/.ssh
```

* Look for files like `id_ed25519` and `id_ed25519.pub`

* If they exist, you can reuse them or create a new one

* Generate a new SSH key using your email:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "MMohamed_786@outlook.com"
```

* Press Enter to accept the default file location

* Optionally enter a passphrase (recommended)

* Start the SSH agent:

```bash
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
```

* Add your SSH key to the agent:

```bash
ssh-add --apple-use-keychain ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

* Copy your public key to the clipboard:

```bash
pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

* Add the key to your GitHub account (username: MMohamed-1-sudo):

* Go to GitHub

* Click your profile picture (top right)

* Go to “Settings”

* Click “SSH and GPG keys”

* Click “New SSH key”

* Title it something like “MacBook - MMohamed-1-sudo”

* Paste the copied key and save

* Test the SSH connection:

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

* You should see a success message mentioning your username: MMohamed-1-sudo

* If your repo is still using HTTPS, switch it to SSH:

```bash
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:MMohamed-1-sudo/your-repo-name.git
```

After this setup, you’ll be able to push and pull without entering your GitHub username and password.
